<div id="trends" class="tab-section">
  <div class="section-header">
    <h2>Historical Trends</h2>
    <span class="tag">2021–2025 · Seed Records · Betting Patterns</span>
  </div>

  <div class="trends-grid">
    <div class="trend-card">
      <div class="trend-matchup" style="color: var(--upset-red);">#12 vs #5</div>
      <div class="trend-win-rate" style="color: var(--upset-red);">35%</div>
      <div class="trend-label">12-seed upset rate all-time</div>
      <div class="trend-bar-bg"><div class="trend-bar-fill" style="width: 35%; background: var(--upset-red);"></div></div>
      <p class="trend-note">At least one 12-seed upset in <strong>33 of the last 39 tournaments.</strong> The lone exception recently: 2023, where all four 5-seeds won. Reality kicked back in 2024 with Grand Canyon & James Madison both winning. Treat every 12-seed matchup as a near-coin-flip.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="trend-card">
      <div class="trend-matchup" style="color: var(--bracket-gold);">#11 vs #6</div>
      <div class="trend-win-rate" style="color: var(--bracket-gold);">38%</div>
      <div class="trend-label">11-seed upset rate all-time</div>
      <div class="trend-bar-bg"><div class="trend-bar-fill" style="width: 38%; background: var(--bracket-gold);"></div></div>
      <p class="trend-note">Historically <strong>more dangerous than the 12 seed.</strong> Over the last five tournaments, 11-seeds have gone 10-10 in round one. NC State's 2024 Final Four run started here. Never zero 11-seeds have advanced since 2004.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="trend-card">
      <div class="trend-matchup" style="color: var(--accent-blue);">#8 vs #9</div>
      <div class="trend-win-rate" style="color: var(--accent-blue);">51%</div>
      <div class="trend-label">9-seed win rate (true coin-flip)</div>
      <div class="trend-bar-bg"><div class="trend-bar-fill" style="width: 51%; background: var(--accent-blue);"></div></div>
      <p class="trend-note">The committee treats these teams as equals. Over 40 years, the <strong>9-seed holds a 76–72 edge</strong> over the 8-seed. Either team can win. Sharp play: look at the spread and recent form rather than seeding.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="trend-card">
      <div class="trend-matchup" style="color: var(--win-green);">#1 Seeds</div>
      <div class="trend-win-rate" style="color: var(--win-green);">98%</div>
      <div class="trend-label">1-seed win rate vs 16-seeds</div>
      <div class="trend-bar-bg"><div class="trend-bar-fill" style="width: 98%; background: var(--win-green);"></div></div>
      <p class="trend-note">Only <strong>2 of 156</strong> 16-seeds have ever won: UMBC over Virginia (2018) and Fairleigh Dickinson over Purdue (2023). With UMBC playing in the First Four this year, the narrative is irresistible — but the odds are still firmly against a repeat.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="trend-card">
      <div class="trend-matchup" style="color: var(--court-wood);">#13 vs #4</div>
      <div class="trend-win-rate" style="color: var(--court-wood);">21%</div>
      <div class="trend-label">13-seed upset rate all-time</div>
      <div class="trend-bar-bg"><div class="trend-bar-fill" style="width: 21%; background: var(--court-wood);"></div></div>
      <p class="trend-note">33 upsets in 157 games. Happened in <strong>2021 (twice), 2022, 2023, 2024</strong> — a hot 5-year run. Prediction markets have 13-over-4 at roughly 50/50 odds for at least one occurring. Conference champions from strong mid-majors are dangerous here.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="trend-card">
      <div class="trend-matchup" style="color: var(--muted);">Defense Wins</div>
      <div class="trend-win-rate" style="color: var(--muted);">Top 20</div>
      <div class="trend-label">Defensive adj. efficiency + Final Four</div>
      <div class="trend-bar-bg"><div class="trend-bar-fill" style="width: 60%; background: var(--muted);"></div></div>
      <p class="trend-note">Since 2012, only <strong>5 Final Four teams</strong> ranked outside the Top 40 in adjusted defensive efficiency. Of 44 national semifinalists, 20 were in the <strong>Top 10 defensively</strong>. Houston (+32 KenPom) and Virginia are this year's defensive anchors.</p>
    </div>
