<!-- ============================================================ UPSETS ============================================================ -->
<div id="upsets" class="tab-section">
  <div class="section-header">
    <h2>Upset Watch</h2>
    <span class="tag">Most Dangerous First-Round Matchups</span>
  </div>

  <div class="upset-grid">

    <div class="upset-card upset-hot">
      <div class="upset-body">
        <div class="upset-matchup">
          <div class="upset-fav">#6 Tennessee</div>
          <div class="upset-arrow">→</div>
          <div class="upset-dog">#11 Miami (OH)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="upset-conf conf-hot">🔥 Top Upset Pick</div>
        <p class="upset-reason"><strong>Miami (Ohio) went 31-0 in the MAC regular season</strong> and plays a 40%-from-three offense with nine different players capable of 20-point games. They enter the tournament as one of the hottest teams in college basketball. Tennessee has been inconsistent in close games. The 11-seed First Four survivor carries genuine Cinderella energy backed by real analytics — not just vibes.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="upset-card upset-warm">
      <div class="upset-body">
        <div class="upset-matchup">
          <div class="upset-fav">#5 Wisconsin</div>
          <div class="upset-arrow">→</div>
          <div class="upset-dog">#12 High Point</div>
        </div>
        <div class="upset-conf conf-warm">⚡ Classic 12-over-5</div>
        <p class="upset-reason"><strong>High Point is riding an 11-game win streak</strong> into the tournament. Wisconsin has been in a 68-65 near-miss mode all season, barely edging quality opponents. Analytics models rate this matchup much closer than the seed differential suggests. 12-seeds win in 35% of first-round games — statistically, picking at least two this tournament is the <em>safe</em> play.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="upset-card upset-warm">
      <div class="upset-body">
        <div class="upset-matchup">
          <div class="upset-fav">#7 Kentucky</div>
          <div class="upset-arrow">→</div>
          <div class="upset-dog">#10 Santa Clara</div>
        </div>
        <div class="upset-conf conf-warm">🔍 Analytics Darling</div>
        <p class="upset-reason"><strong>Santa Clara holds a top-40 national résumé</strong> and had an 88% at-large probability entering Selection Sunday. They beat Saint Mary's — a projected 7-seed — in the WCC semis. Kentucky (21-13) barely squeaked into the field. The Broncos' high-efficiency offense could expose a Wildcats team that struggled against quality competition all year. 10-seeds beat 7-seeds nearly 40% of the time.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="upset-card upset-hot">
      <div class="upset-body">
        <div class="upset-matchup">
          <div class="upset-fav">#6 Louisville</div>
          <div class="upset-arrow">→</div>
          <div class="upset-dog">#11 South Florida</div>
        </div>
        <div class="upset-conf conf-hot">🔥 Hot Hand Alert</div>
        <p class="upset-reason"><strong>South Florida won the American Athletic Conference title</strong> and enters on a 7-game winning streak. Analytics models rate USF higher than their 11-seed suggests in underlying efficiency metrics. Louisville has been shaky against teams that can defend and rebound — both hallmarks of the Bulls' game plan.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="upset-card upset-cool">
      <div class="upset-body">
        <div class="upset-matchup">
          <div class="upset-fav">#9 Iowa</div>
          <div class="upset-arrow">→</div>
          <div class="upset-dog">#8 Clemson</div>
        </div>
        <div class="upset-conf conf-cool">📊 Coin-Flip</div>
        <p class="upset-reason">The <strong>8 vs 9 matchup is a statistical coin-flip</strong> — 9-seeds hold a 76-72 all-time edge. Clemson played its way to an 8-seed through a tough ACC. Iowa is tournament-tested. Either outcome is nearly 50/50, making this a value play on Iowa's underdog moneyline if you can find a favorable number.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="upset-card upset-cool">
      <div class="upset-body">
        <div class="upset-matchup">
          <div class="upset-fav">#4 Nebraska</div>
          <div class="upset-arrow">→</div>
          <div class="upset-dog">#13 Troy</div>
        </div>
        <div class="upset-conf conf-cool">📈 Watch the Narrative</div>
        <p class="upset-reason"><strong>Nebraska has never won an NCAA Tournament game</strong> in program history, which creates massive narrative pressure. Fred Hoiberg's 26-5 team is historically their best, but 13-seeds win 21% of the time. Troy won their conference tournament with momentum. <em>Nebraska historically chokes on this stage</em> — and Troy's style of play (high-pressure defense) could be the exact nightmare matchup for a first-timer.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="upset-card upset-warm">
      <div class="upset-body">
        <div class="upset-matchup">
          <div class="upset-fav">#1 Florida</div>
          <div class="upset-arrow">vs</div>
          <div class="upset-dog">#2 Houston (E8)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="upset-conf conf-warm">🏟 Location Alert</div>
        <p class="upset-reason"><strong>The South Region Final is in Houston.</strong> If Florida and Houston both advance to the Elite Eight, the Cougars would essentially be playing a home game. Houston under Kelvin Sampson is historically a defensive juggernaut (+32 KenPom). The environment could be transformative. Consider Houston's futures odds as strong value given this geographical advantage.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

